We can see we have three different type of wine and 14 variables to describe them. In total 178 observation. We now normalize the variables cause they have different scales:

x.stand=scale(x)
boxplot(x.stand)

Next step we will examining the relationship between variables:

library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
wine_matrix <- data.matrix(x.stand, rownames.force = NA)
M <- cor(wine_matrix)
corrplot(M, method = "number", number.cex = 0.5, order="hclust")

From the correlation matrix we can see that dataset contains some highly correlated features, eg. flavanoids and total phenols (0.86). The highest dependencies (over 0.6) are mainly positive.

Then, we check if the dataset contains outliers through interquartile range statistic:

vars <- c(colnames(x.stand))
Outliers <- c()
for(i in vars){
  max <- quantile(x.stand[,i], 0.75) + (IQR(x.stand[,i]) * 1.5 )
  min <- quantile(x.stand[,i], 0.25) - (IQR(x.stand[,i]) * 1.5 )
  idx <- which(x.stand[i] < min | x.stand[,i] > max)
  print(paste(i, length(idx), sep=' ')) # printing variable and number of potential outliers 
  Outliers <- c(Outliers, idx) 
  }

We decide to keep them. In order to choose the clustering algorithm best fitted to the data, owe must consider characteristics of the dataset. From initial analysis,we know that we deal with continuous variables and most of them are correlated (mainly positively). Dataset doesn’t contain worrisome outliers.

##Prediagnostic We use the Hopkins statistic in order to check wheather data can be clustered and also to choose the optimal number of clusters.

library(clustertend)
library(factoextra)
## Loading required package: ggplot2

get_clust_tendency(x.stand,3, graph=TRUE, gradient=list(low="red", mid="white", high="blue"))

We obtain H=0.656.

We now try to find the best number of clusters with silhouette statistic and apply it to three flat clustering algorithms: k-means, PAM and CLARA, hierarchical clustering and fuzzy clustering.

library(gridExtra)
a <- fviz_nbclust(x.stand, FUNcluster = kmeans, method = "silhouette") + theme_classic()

## *** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
##                 In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
##                 significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
##                 index second differences plot. 
## 

## *** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
##                 In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex
##                 second differences plot) that corresponds to a significant increase of the value of
##                 the measure. 
##

##Hierarchial Clustering

hc <- eclust(x.stand, k=3, FUNcluster="hclust", hc_metric="euclidean", hc_method = "ward.D2")
plot(hc, cex=0.6, hang=-1, main = "Dendrogram of HAC")
rect.hclust(hc, k=3, border='red')

table(hc$cluster,wine$V1)

##Spectral analysis without packages

nodes <- dim(x.stand)[1]
S <- matrix(NA,nrow=nodes,ncol=nodes) #similarity matrix with gaussin karnel 
sigma <- 1.5
for(i in 1:nodes){
  for(j in 1:nodes){
    S[i,j] <- exp(-sum((x.stand[i,] - x.stand[j,])^2)/(2*sigma^2))
  }
}
#degree matrix 
S_degree <- rowSums(S)
#Laplacian matrix 
Laplacian <- diag(S_degree) - S
normalized_Laplacian <- diag(S_degree^(-1/2)) %*% S %*% diag(S_degree^(-1/2))
ev <- eigen(Laplacian)
e <- kmeans(ev$vectors[,which.min(ev$values)],3)$cluster
table(e, wine$V1)
##    
## e    1  2  3
##   1  4 29 48
##   2  4  0  0
##   3 51 42  0

It performs weaker than the others method. We attribute can this anomaly to the curse of dimensionality: 13 dimensions for only 178 points.
